      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The namespace Keyword vs the module Keyword"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TypeScript's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "namespace",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "module",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " keywords are "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "identical",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " at the type level \u2014 TypeScript just aliased "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "namespace",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as the preferred term because "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "module",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " was confusing with ES modules. In "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ".d.ts",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " files you may still see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "declare module 'name'",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for ambient module declarations."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// These are identical at the TypeScript level:\nnamespace Utils { export function clamp(n: number, lo: number, hi: number): number { return Math.min(hi, Math.max(lo, n)); } }\nmodule  Utils { export function clamp(n: number, lo: number, hi: number): number { return Math.min(hi, Math.max(lo, n)); } }\n\n// 'namespace' is the modern spelling \u2014 prefer it\n// 'module' as a declaration keyword exists only for compatibility\n\n// Contrast: 'declare module \"name\"' \u2014 this is an AMBIENT MODULE declaration\n// (different from the namespace/module keyword above)\ndeclare module 'lodash' {\n  export function debounce<T extends (...a: unknown[]) => unknown>(fn: T, ms: number): T;\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Merging Namespaces"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Namespaces support "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "declaration merging",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 multiple "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "namespace",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " blocks with the same name are merged into one. This is used to add properties to enums or to extend a class with static members."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Merging with an enum \u2014 add utility functions\nenum Status { Active = 'active', Inactive = 'inactive' }\n\nnamespace Status {\n  export function isActive(s: Status): boolean { return s === Status.Active; }\n  export function values(): Status[] { return [Status.Active, Status.Inactive]; }\n}\n\nconsole.log(Status.isActive(Status.Active)); // true\nconsole.log(Status.values());                // ['active', 'inactive']\n\n// Merging with a function \u2014 add properties to a function\nfunction greet(name: string): string { return \\`Hello, \\${name}!\\`; }\nnamespace greet {\n  export const defaultName = 'World';\n}\nconsole.log(greet(greet.defaultName)); // 'Hello, World!'\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Namespaces Compile To"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Understanding the emitted JavaScript helps explain the behaviour. A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "namespace",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " block compiles to an IIFE that extends (or creates) a plain object on the global scope \u2014 or as a local variable if the namespace is inside a module."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// TypeScript source\nnamespace Geometry {\n  export interface Point { x: number; y: number; }\n  export function distance(a: Point, b: Point): number {\n    return Math.sqrt((b.x - a.x) ** 2 + (b.y - a.y) ** 2);\n  }\n}\n\n// Compiled JavaScript output (CommonJS/IIFE style)\nvar Geometry;\n(function (Geometry) {\n  function distance(a, b) {\n    return Math.sqrt(Math.pow(b.x - a.x, 2) + Math.pow(b.y - a.y, 2));\n  }\n  Geometry.distance = distance;\n})(Geometry || (Geometry = {}));\n\n// The IIFE pattern means:\n// - If Geometry already exists (multi-file merge), it is extended\n// - If Geometry doesn't exist, it is created as an empty object\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Namespace Import Alias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TypeScript allows an import alias for a namespace (or any other symbol) using the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import =",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " syntax. This is different from ES module imports \u2014 it is TypeScript-specific and works in script mode too."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "namespace App.Services.Http {\n  export class Client {\n    get(url: string): Promise<unknown> {\n      return fetch(url).then(r => r.json());\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// Without alias \u2014 verbose\nconst c1 = new App.Services.Http.Client();\n\n// With alias \u2014 much shorter\nimport HttpClient = App.Services.Http.Client;\nconst c2 = new HttpClient();\n\n// Namespaces can also alias other namespaces:\nnamespace Http = App.Services.Http;\nconst c3 = new Http.Client();\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical Use in Modern Angular \u2014 Declaration Merging Only"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In modern Angular projects, the only common use of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "namespace",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "declaration merging with enums",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to add utility methods. All other namespace usage should be replaced with ES modules."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// user-status.ts \u2014 practical real-world pattern\nexport enum UserStatus {\n  Active   = 'active',\n  Suspended = 'suspended',\n  Deleted  = 'deleted'\n}\n\nexport namespace UserStatus {\n  export function label(status: UserStatus): string {\n    switch (status) {\n      case UserStatus.Active:    return 'Active';\n      case UserStatus.Suspended: return 'Suspended';\n      case UserStatus.Deleted:   return 'Deleted';\n    }\n  }\n\n  export function isBanned(status: UserStatus): boolean {\n    return status === UserStatus.Suspended || status === UserStatus.Deleted;\n  }\n\n  export function all(): UserStatus[] {\n    return [UserStatus.Active, UserStatus.Suspended, UserStatus.Deleted];\n  }\n}\n\n// consumer.ts\nimport { UserStatus } from './user-status';\n\nconst status = UserStatus.Active;\nconsole.log(UserStatus.label(status));    // 'Active'\nconsole.log(UserStatus.isBanned(status)); // false\nUserStatus.all().forEach(s => console.log(UserStatus.label(s)));\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ambient Namespace for Global Libraries \u2014 Worked Example"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Suppose you add "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Chart.js",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (or any analytics library) via a CDN "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "<script>",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tag instead of npm. TypeScript won't know about it. An ambient "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "declare namespace",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tells the compiler the shape:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// typings/charting.d.ts \u2014 minimal ambient declaration for a CDN script\ndeclare namespace Charting {\n  interface DataSet {\n    label: string;\n    data: number[];\n    backgroundColor?: string;\n  }\n\n  interface ChartConfig {\n    type: 'bar' | 'line' | 'pie';\n    labels: string[];\n    datasets: DataSet[];\n  }\n\n  class Chart {\n    constructor(canvas: HTMLCanvasElement, config: ChartConfig);\n    update(): void;\n    destroy(): void;\n  }\n}\n\n// component using the CDN-loaded global\n// (no import statement \u2014 the library is on window.Charting)\n@Component({ selector: 'app-chart', template: '<canvas #canvas></canvas>' })\nexport class ChartComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {\n  @ViewChild('canvas') canvasRef!: ElementRef<HTMLCanvasElement>;\n  private chart!: Charting.Chart;\n\n  ngOnInit(): void {\n    this.chart = new Charting.Chart(this.canvasRef.nativeElement, {\n      type: 'bar',\n      labels: ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar'],\n      datasets: [{ label: 'Sales', data: [120, 85, 200] }]\n    });\n  }\n\n  ngOnDestroy(): void { this.chart.destroy(); }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Migrating from Namespaces to ES Modules"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The migration path is mechanical and straightforward:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BEFORE \u2014 namespace approach\nnamespace Validation {\n  export class EmailValidator {\n    isValid(s: string): boolean { return s.includes('@'); }\n  }\n  export class LengthValidator {\n    isValid(s: string, min: number, max: number): boolean {\n      return s.length >= min && s.length <= max;\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// AFTER \u2014 ES module approach\n// src/validators/email.validator.ts\nexport class EmailValidator {\n  isValid(s: string): boolean { return s.includes('@'); }\n}\n\n// src/validators/length.validator.ts\nexport class LengthValidator {\n  isValid(s: string, min: number, max: number): boolean {\n    return s.length >= min && s.length <= max;\n  }\n}\n\n// src/validators/index.ts \u2014 barrel\nexport { EmailValidator } from './email.validator';\nexport { LengthValidator } from './length.validator';\n\n// Consumer\nimport { EmailValidator, LengthValidator } from './validators';\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Angular's compiler never reads namespace-based code at build time \u2014 it only understands ES modules. Always use ES modules in Angular projects unless writing ambient declarations for non-module scripts."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing Code That Uses Namespaces"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Namespace declarations are accessible without importing, so testing them is simpler \u2014 but structurally messy for larger projects:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// In a test file that does NOT use modules (script mode):\n/// <reference path=\"../validation.ts\" />\n\ndescribe('Validation.EmailValidator', () => {\n  let validator: Validation.EmailValidator;\n\n  beforeEach(() => { validator = new Validation.EmailValidator(); });\n\n  it('accepts valid emails', () => {\n    expect(validator.isValid('alice@example.com')).toBe(true);\n  });\n\n  it('rejects missing @', () => {\n    expect(validator.isValid('notanemail')).toBe(false);\n  });\n});\n\n// After migrating to ES modules, testing becomes standard:\nimport { EmailValidator } from '../validators/email.validator';\n\ndescribe('EmailValidator', () => {\n  it('validates email', () => {\n    expect(new EmailValidator().isValid('a@b.com')).toBe(true);\n  });\n});\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Namespaces group declarations under a shared global name \u2014 no import needed, but no isolation either."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "They compile to an IIFE that populates a plain JavaScript object."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "declare namespace",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " is still used today in "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ".d.ts",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " files for global scripts and legacy UMD libraries."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "For new Angular code, always use ES modules \u2014 they tree-shake, lazy-load, and scale better."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Namespace declaration merging is useful for extending enums with utility methods."
